article.description: Doneeka Hodges scored 20 points to lead No. 18 LSU to its seventh straight win, 97-47 over SE Louisiana on Saturday.
article.headline: Tigers forced 27 turnovers
article.linkText: No. 18 LSU routs SE Louisiana, wins 7th straight
article.story:
BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- With a six-game winning streak on the
line, LSU coach Sue Gunter got what she wanted -- tough play even
against an underdog.

On Saturday, No. 16 LSU beat Southeastern Louisiana 97-47.

"No matter who your opponent is, you have to go out and
execute. That is the bottom line," Gunter said.

Starters led the Tigers (8-2) with Doneeka Hodges scoring 20
points, Seimone Augustus 15 and Temeka Johnson 14.

But all 11 LSU players, with reserves Scholanda Hoston and
Treynelle Clavelle combining for 23 of the Tigers' 40 bench points.

"The play we got from everyone who came into the game was
exactly what we as coaches hope will happen," Gunter said.

Hoston, who played just one minute in the first half after
picking up two quick fouls, scored 13 points to end in double
figures for the fifth consecutive game, while Clavelle was 5-for-5
from the floor and scored 10 points, her first double-figure outing
at LSU.

LSU forced Southeastern Louisiana (3-3) into 27 turnovers and
scored 49 points off those miscues.

The Lions kept it close in the opening minutes until the LSU
went on a 10-0 run to make it 26-10 with 7:36 left in the first
half.

LSU went on an 11-0 run later in the half to make it 39-14 and
led 43-19 at the break.

Tish Guy scored 11 points for the Lions, who last beat LSU in
1981.
